<paragraph id="D50A3774993E37E920A1EDFDA566DBCF" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<taxonomicName id="66DD422F0C6D82CE1806AE43CFD9EFA4" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia arborea" order="Myrtales" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arborea">
<emphasis id="AD7D6E85647383801E28B2263FFBD2A6" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Conostegia arborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by its leaves with dentate margins, abaxial indument of sessile and stipitate stellate hairs and especially by its apiculate calyptra apices. The amount of indument on floral buds is variable. The flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="011C207B96F41F7ECD6AB2FBADC6DC35" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia arborea" order="Myrtales" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arborea">
<emphasis id="6D7A2470D61D83E9EE529D90E69D0CA6" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Conostegia arborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been reported to have a good fragrance (
<emphasis id="0A4C4A5309EBF181F6D1F9ADE87BA465" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Ventura 1141</emphasis>
- NY).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
